03981nam a22005655i 9780822394921DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223949217 a10.1515/97808223949212doi  a(DE-B1597)553523  a(OCoLC)770603672  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS3569.E316bW43 2012 7aLIT0041602bisacsh04a814/.542231 aSedgwick, Eve Kosofsky, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Weather in Proust /cEve Kosofsky Sedgwick; Jonathan Goldberg, Michael Moon. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b37 color illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSeries Q00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tEditor's Introduction -- tThe Weather in Proust -- tCavafy, Proust, and the Queer Little Gods -- tMaking Things, Practicing Emptiness -- tMelanie Klein and the Difference Affect Makes -- tAffect Theory and Theory of Mind -- tAnality: News from the Front -- tMaking Gay Meanings -- tThinking through Queer Theory -- tReality and Realization -- tFigure Credits -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Weather in Proust gathers pieces written by the eminent critic and theorist Eve Kosofsky Sedgwick in the last decade of her life, as she worked toward a book on Proust. This book takes its title from the first essay, a startlingly original interpretation of Proust. By way of Neoplatonism, Buddhism, and the work of Melanie Klein, Sedgwick establishes the sense of refreshment and surprise that the author of the Recherche affords his readers. Proust also figures in pieces on the poetry of C. P. Cavafy, object relations, affect theory, and Sedgwick's textile art practices. More explicitly connected to her role as a pioneering queer theorist are an exuberant attack against reactionary refusals of the work of Guy Hocquenghem and talks in which she lays out her central ideas about sexuality and her concerns about the direction of US queer theory. Sedgwick lived for more than a dozen years with a diagnosis of terminal cancer; its implications informed her later writing and thinking, as well as her spiritual and artistic practices. In the book's final and most personal essay, she reflects on the realization of her impending death. Featuring thirty-seven color images of her art, The Weather in Proust offers a comprehensive view of Sedgwick's later work, underscoring its diversity and coherence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / LGBT.2bisacsh1 aGoldberg, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoon, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822394921zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822394921423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822394921.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles